### 📄 Model — Item.java — The Database Blueprint

The model class represents a **database table**. Every field in the class becomes a column in the table.

```java
@Entity           ← "This class = a database table"
@Table(name = "items")   ← "The table is named 'items'"
public class Item {

    @Id
    @GeneratedValue(strategy = GenerationType.IDENTITY)
    private Long id;          ← Auto-generated ID (1, 2, 3...)

    @Column(nullable = false)
    private String name;      ← Item name, cannot be empty

    private String description;   ← Optional description

    @Column(nullable = false)
    private String category;  ← Category, cannot be empty

    private LocalDateTime createdAt;  ← When it was created
}
```

When your app starts, Hibernate reads this class and creates this table in MySQL:

```
items table in MySQL:
┌────┬──────────────────┬─────────────────┬─────────────┬─────────────────────┐
│ id │ name             │ description     │ category    │ created_at          │
├────┼──────────────────┼─────────────────┼─────────────┼─────────────────────┤
│  1 │ Wireless Mouse   │ Ergonomic mouse │ Electronics │ 2025-07-28 09:00:00 │
│  2 │ USB Keyboard     │ Mechanical KB   │ Electronics │ 2025-07-28 10:00:00 │
└────┴──────────────────┴─────────────────┴─────────────┴─────────────────────┘
```

---

### 📄 DTO — ItemDTO.java — The Data Transfer Object

**Why do we need DTO when we already have the Model?**

Think of it this way. The **Model** is your internal database record — it might have sensitive fields or fields you don't want to expose. The **DTO** is what you show to the outside world.

Real example: Your `User` model might have a `password` field. You never want to send the password in an API response. So your `UserDTO` has everything except the password.

In our case, `ItemDTO` also contains **validation rules**:

```java
public class ItemDTO {

    private Long id;

    @NotBlank(message = "Name is required")
    @Size(max = 150, message = "Name must not exceed 150 characters")
    private String name;       ← Must not be blank, max 150 chars

    private String description;   ← Optional

    @NotBlank(message = "Category is required")
    private String category;  ← Must not be blank

    private LocalDateTime createdAt;
}
```

So when someone sends a POST request to create an item, if they forget to include the `name`, Spring automatically returns an error: `"Name is required"`. You don't have to write that check manually.

---

### 📄 Repository — ItemRepository.java — Database Operations

The repository is your **direct line to the database**. You define what queries you need, and Spring automatically implements them for you.

```java
@Repository
public interface ItemRepository extends JpaRepository<Item, Long> {

    List<Item> findByCategory(String category);
    // Spring reads this method name and generates:
    // SELECT * FROM items WHERE category = ?

    List<Item> findByNameContainingIgnoreCase(String name);
    // SELECT * FROM items WHERE LOWER(name) LIKE LOWER('%name%')

    boolean existsByNameAndCategory(String name, String category);
    // SELECT COUNT(*) > 0 FROM items WHERE name=? AND category=?
}
```

By extending `JpaRepository`, you automatically get these methods **for free** without writing any code:

```
save(item)         → INSERT or UPDATE
findById(id)       → SELECT WHERE id = ?
findAll()          → SELECT * FROM items
deleteById(id)     → DELETE WHERE id = ?
existsById(id)     → SELECT COUNT(*) WHERE id = ?
count()            → SELECT COUNT(*) FROM items
```

---

### 📄 Service — The Business Logic Brain

The service layer is where the **actual work happens**. The controller receives the request, the repository talks to the database — but the service **decides what to do**.

**ItemService.java** — just defines what operations exist (interface):
```java
public interface ItemService {
    ItemDTO createItem(ItemDTO itemDTO);
    ItemDTO getItemById(Long id);
    List<ItemDTO> getAllItems();
    ItemDTO updateItem(Long id, ItemDTO itemDTO);
    void deleteItem(Long id);
}
```

**ItemServiceImpl.java** — actually implements those operations:

```java
public ItemDTO createItem(ItemDTO itemDTO) {

    // Step 1: Convert DTO to Model (Entity)
    Item item = Item.builder()
            .name(itemDTO.getName())
            .description(itemDTO.getDescription())
            .category(itemDTO.getCategory())
            .createdAt(LocalDateTime.now())
            .build();

    // Step 2: Save to database
    Item saved = itemRepository.save(item);

    // Step 3: Convert saved Model back to DTO and return
    return toDTO(saved);
}
```

And for fetching:
```java
public ItemDTO getItemById(Long id) {

    // Try to find in database
    Item item = itemRepository.findById(id)
            .orElseThrow(() -> new ItemNotFoundException(id));
    // If not found → throw error "Item not found with id: X"
    // If found → convert to DTO and return

    return toDTO(item);
}
```

