### 📄 Controller — ItemController.java — The API Doorway

The controller is the **front door** of your service. Every URL endpoint lives here. When someone makes an HTTP request, it lands in this class first.

```java
@RestController           ← "This class handles HTTP requests"
@RequestMapping("/api/items")  ← All URLs start with /api/items
public class ItemController {

    @PostMapping          ← Handles POST /api/items
    public ResponseEntity<ApiResponse<ItemDTO>> createItem(
            @RequestBody ItemDTO itemDTO) {   ← Read JSON from request body
        ItemDTO created = itemService.createItem(itemDTO);
        return ResponseEntity.status(201).body(...);  ← Return 201 Created
    }

    @GetMapping("/{id}")  ← Handles GET /api/items/5
    public ResponseEntity<ApiResponse<ItemDTO>> getItemById(
            @PathVariable Long id) {   ← 5 becomes the 'id' variable
        ItemDTO item = itemService.getItemById(id);
        return ResponseEntity.ok(...);  ← Return 200 OK
    }

    @DeleteMapping("/{id}")  ← Handles DELETE /api/items/5
    public ResponseEntity<ApiResponse<Void>> deleteItem(
            @PathVariable Long id) {
        itemService.deleteItem(id);
        return ResponseEntity.ok(...);
    }
}
```

The **flow of every request** is:

```
Postman/Swagger → Controller → Service → Repository → MySQL Database
                                                              ↓
Postman/Swagger ← Controller ← Service ← Repository ← MySQL Database
```

