### 📄 Exception Handling — Clean Error Responses

Without exception handling, if something goes wrong, Java would return a massive ugly error with 50 lines of stack trace. We don't want that.

**ItemNotFoundException.java:**
```java
public class ItemNotFoundException extends RuntimeException {
    public ItemNotFoundException(Long id) {
        super("Item not found with id: " + id);
    }
}
```

**GlobalExceptionHandler.java** catches all errors and returns clean JSON:

```java
@ExceptionHandler(ItemNotFoundException.class)
public ResponseEntity<ApiResponse<Void>> handleItemNotFound(ItemNotFoundException ex) {
    return ResponseEntity.status(404).body(ApiResponse.error(ex.getMessage()));
}
```

So instead of a scary Java error, the client gets this clean response:
```json
{
  "success": false,
  "message": "Item not found with id: 99",
  "data": null
}
```

---

### 📄 ApiResponse.java — Consistent Response Wrapper

Every API response looks the same — success or failure:

```java
// Success response looks like:
{
  "success": true,
  "message": "Item created successfully",
  "data": {
    "id": 1,
    "name": "Wireless Mouse",
