## Part 10 — Full Request Flow Example

Let's trace exactly what happens when you create a new item:

```
YOU (Swagger/Postman)
Send: POST http://localhost:8081/api/items
Body: { "name": "Wireless Mouse", "category": "Electronics" }
Header: Authorization: Bearer eyJhbGc...
           │
           ▼
JwtAuthFilter.java
  → Reads the Bearer token
  → Validates it using secret key
  → Valid! Proceed.
           │
           ▼
ItemController.java → createItem() method
  → Receives the JSON
  → Spring validates: name not blank? ✓  category not blank? ✓
  → Calls itemService.createItem(itemDTO)
           │
           ▼
ItemServiceImpl.java → createItem() method
  → Converts DTO to Item model
  → Sets createdAt = now
  → Calls itemRepository.save(item)
           │
           ▼
ItemRepository.java
  → Runs: INSERT INTO items (name, description, category, created_at)
          VALUES ('Wireless Mouse', null, 'Electronics', now())
           │
           ▼
MySQL Database
  → Saves the row
  → Returns the saved row with auto-generated id=1
           │
           ▼ (response travels back up)
ItemServiceImpl → converts Item back to ItemDTO
           │
           ▼
ItemController → wraps in ApiResponse
           │
           ▼
YOU receive:
{
  "success": true,
  "message": "Item created successfully",
  "data": {
    "id": 1,
    "name": "Wireless Mouse",
    "category": "Electronics",
    "createdAt": "2025-07-28T09:00:00"
  }
}
HTTP Status: 201 Created
```

